# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chromatography-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In chemical analysis, **chromatography** is a laboratory technique for the separation of a mixture into its components.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The mixture is dissolved in a fluid solvent (gas or liquid) called the *mobile phase*, which carries it through a system (a column, a capillary tube, a plate, or a sheet) on which a material called the *stationary phase* is fixed.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The separation is based on the differential partitioning between the mobile and the stationary phases.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Subtle differences in a compound's partition coefficient result in differential retention on the stationary phase and thus affect the separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Chromatography may be *preparative* or *analytical*.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The purpose of preparative chromatography is to separate the components of a mixture for later use, and is thus a form of purification.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This process is associated with higher costs due to its mode of production.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Analytical chromatography is done normally with smaller amounts of material and is for establishing the presence or measuring the relative proportions of analytes in a mixture.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The two types are not mutually exclusive.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Chromatography, pronounced /ˌkroʊməˈtɒɡrəfi/, is derived from Greek χρῶμα *chrōma*, which means "color", and γράφειν *gráphein*, which means "to write".
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The combination of these two terms was directly inherited from the invention of the technique first used to separate biological pigments.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The method was developed by botanist Mikhail Tsvet in 1901–1905 in the universities of Kazan and Warsaw.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] He developed the technique and coined the term *chromatography* in the first decade of the 20th century, primarily for the separation of plant pigments such as chlorophyll, carotenes, and xanthophylls.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Since these components separate in bands of different colors (green, orange, and yellow, respectively) they directly inspired the name of the technique.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] New types of chromatography developed during the 1930s and 1940s made the technique useful for many separation processes.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Chromatography technique developed substantially as a result of the work of Archer John Porter Martin and Richard Laurence Millington Synge during the 1940s and 1950s, for which they won the 1952 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] They established the principles and basic techniques of partition chromatography, and their work encouraged the rapid development of several chromatographic methods: paper chromatography, gas chromatography, and what would become known as high-performance liquid chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Since then, the technology has advanced rapidly.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Researchers found that the main principles of Tsvet's chromatography could be applied in many different ways, resulting in the different varieties of chromatography described below.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Advances are continually improving the technical performance of chromatography, allowing the separation of increasingly similar molecules.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Chromatography is based on the concept of partition coefficient.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Any solute partitions between two immiscible solvents.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] When one make one solvent immobile (by adsorption on a solid support matrix) and another mobile it results in most common applications of chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] If the matrix support, or stationary phase, is polar (e.g., cellulose, silica etc.) it is forward phase chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Otherwise this technique is known as reversed phase, where a non-polar stationary phase (e.g., non-polar derivative of C-18) is used.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Column chromatography is a separation technique in which the stationary bed is within a tube.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Differences in rates of movement through the medium are calculated to different retention times of the sample.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Clark Still introduced a modified version of column chromatography called *flash column chromatography* (flash).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The technique is very similar to the traditional column chromatography, except that the solvent is driven through the column by applying positive pressure.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This allowed most separations to be performed in less than 20 minutes, with improved separations compared to the old method.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Modern flash chromatography systems are sold as pre-packed plastic cartridges, and the solvent is pumped through the cartridge.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Systems may also be linked with detectors and fraction collectors providing automation.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The introduction of gradient pumps resulted in quicker separations and less solvent usage.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In expanded bed adsorption, a fluidized bed is used, rather than a solid phase made by a packed bed.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This allows omission of initial clearing steps such as centrifugation and filtration, for culture broths or slurries of broken cells.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Phosphocellulose chromatography utilizes the binding affinity of many DNA-binding proteins for phosphocellulose.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The stronger a protein's interaction with DNA, the higher the salt concentration needed to elute that protein.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Paper chromatography is a technique that involves placing a small dot or line of sample solution onto a strip of *chromatography paper*.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The paper is placed in a container with a shallow layer of solvent and sealed.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] As the solvent rises through the paper, it meets the sample mixture, which starts to travel up the paper with the solvent.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This paper is made of cellulose, a polar substance, and the compounds within the mixture travel further if they are less polar.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] More polar substances bond with the cellulose paper more quickly, and therefore do not travel as far.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Thin-layer chromatography (TLC) is a widely employed laboratory technique used to separate different biochemicals on the basis of their relative attractions to the stationary and mobile phases.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] However, instead of using a stationary phase of paper, it involves a stationary phase of a thin layer of adsorbent like silica gel, alumina, or cellulose on a flat, inert substrate.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] TLC is very versatile; multiple samples can be separated simultaneously on the same layer, making it very useful for screening applications such as testing drug levels and water purity.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Possibility of cross-contamination is low since each separation is performed on a new layer.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Compared to paper, it has the advantage of faster runs, better separations, better quantitative analysis, and the choice between different adsorbents.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] For even better resolution and faster separation that utilizes less solvent, high-performance TLC can be used.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] An older popular use had been to differentiate chromosomes by observing distance in gel (separation of was a separate step).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The basic principle of displacement chromatography is: A molecule with a high affinity for the chromatography matrix (the displacer) competes effectively for binding sites, and thus displaces all molecules with lesser affinities.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] There are distinct differences between displacement and elution chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In elution mode, substances typically emerge from a column in narrow, Gaussian peaks.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Wide separation of peaks, preferably to baseline, is desired for maximum purification.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The speed at which any component of a mixture travels down the column in elution mode depends on many factors.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] But for two substances to travel at different speeds, and thereby be resolved, there must be substantial differences in some interaction between the biomolecules and the chromatography matrix.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Operating parameters are adjusted to maximize the effect of this difference.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In many cases, baseline separation of the peaks can be achieved only with gradient elution and low column loadings.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Thus, two drawbacks to elution mode chromatography, especially at the preparative scale, are operational complexity, due to gradient solvent pumping, and low throughput, due to low column loadings.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Displacement chromatography has advantages over elution chromatography in that components are resolved into consecutive zones of pure substances rather than "peaks".
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Because the process takes advantage of the nonlinearity of the isotherms, a larger column feed can be separated on a given column with the purified components recovered at significantly higher concentrations.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Gas chromatography (GC), also sometimes known as gas-liquid chromatography, (GLC), is a separation technique in which the mobile phase is a gas.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Gas chromatographic separation is always carried out in a column, which is typically "packed" or "capillary".
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Packed columns are the routine workhorses of gas chromatography, being cheaper and easier to use and often giving adequate performance.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Capillary columns generally give far superior resolution and although more expensive are becoming widely used, especially for complex mixtures.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Further, capillary columns can be split into three classes: porous layer open tubular (PLOT), wall-coated open tubular (WCOT) and support-coated open tubular (SCOT) columns.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] PLOT columns are unique in a way that the stationary phase is adsorbed to the column walls, while WCOT columns have a stationary phase that is chemically bonded to the walls.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] SCOT columns are in a way the combination of the two types mentioned in a way that they have support particles adhered to column walls, but those particles have liquid phase chemically bonded onto them.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Both types of column are made from non-adsorbent and chemically inert materials.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Stainless steel and glass are the usual materials for packed columns and quartz or fused silica for capillary columns.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Gas chromatography is based on a partition equilibrium of analyte between a solid or viscous liquid stationary phase (often a liquid silicone-based material) and a mobile gas (most often helium).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The stationary phase is adhered to the inside of a small-diameter (commonly 0.53 – 0.18mm inside diameter) glass or fused-silica tube (a capillary column) or a solid matrix inside a larger metal tube (a packed column).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It is also used extensively in chemistry research.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Liquid chromatography (LC) is a separation technique in which the mobile phase is a liquid.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It can be carried out either in a column or a plane.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Present day liquid chromatography that generally utilizes very small packing particles and a relatively high pressure is referred to as high-performance liquid chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In HPLC the sample is forced by a liquid at high pressure (the mobile phase) through a column that is packed with a stationary phase composed of irregularly or spherically shaped particles, a porous monolithic layer, or a porous membrane.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Monoliths are "sponge-like chromatographic media" and are made up of an unending block of organic or inorganic parts.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] HPLC is historically divided into two different sub-classes based on the polarity of the mobile and stationary phases.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] A specialization of liquid chromatography is nano-liquid chromatography (nano-LC).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Supercritical fluid chromatography is a separation technique in which the mobile phase is a fluid above and relatively close to its critical temperature and pressure.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Affinity chromatography is based on selective non-covalent interaction between an analyte and specific molecules.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It is very specific, but not very robust.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It is often used in biochemistry in the purification of proteins bound to tags.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] These fusion proteins are labeled with compounds such as His-tags, biotin or antigens, which bind to the stationary phase specifically.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] After purification, these tags are usually removed and the pure protein is obtained.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Affinity chromatography often utilizes a biomolecule's affinity for the cations of a metal (Zn, Cu, Fe, etc.).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Columns are often manually prepared and could be designed specifically for the proteins of interest.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Traditional affinity columns are used as a preparative step to flush out unwanted biomolecules, or as a primary step in analyzing a protein with unknown physical properties.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] However, liquid chromatography techniques exist that do utilize affinity chromatography properties.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Immobilized metal affinity chromatography (IMAC) is useful to separate the aforementioned molecules based on the relative affinity for the metal.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Often these columns can be loaded with different metals to create a column with a targeted affinity.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Ion exchange chromatography (usually referred to as ion chromatography) uses an ion exchange mechanism to separate analytes based on their respective charges.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It is usually performed in columns but can also be useful in planar mode.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Ion exchange chromatography uses a charged stationary phase to separate charged compounds including anions, cations, amino acids, peptides, and proteins.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In conventional methods the stationary phase is an ion-exchange resin that carries charged functional groups that interact with oppositely charged groups of the compound to retain.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] There are two types of ion exchange chromatography: Cation-Exchange and Anion-Exchange.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In the Cation-Exchange Chromatography the stationary phase has negative charge and the exchangeable ion is a cation, whereas, in the Anion-Exchange Chromatography the stationary phase has positive charge and the exchangeable ion is an anion.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Ion exchange chromatography is commonly used to purify proteins using FPLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Size-exclusion chromatography (SEC) is also known as *gel permeation chromatography* (GPC) or *gel filtration chromatography* and separates molecules according to their size (or more accurately according to their hydrodynamic diameter or hydrodynamic volume).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Smaller molecules are able to enter the pores of the media and, therefore, molecules are trapped and removed from the flow of the mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The average residence time in the pores depends upon the effective size of the analyte molecules.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] However, molecules that are larger than the average pore size of the packing are excluded and thus suffer essentially no retention; such species are the first to be eluted.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It is generally a low-resolution chromatography technique and thus it is often reserved for the final, "polishing" step of a purification.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It is also useful for determining the tertiary structure and quaternary structure of purified proteins, especially since it can be carried out under native solution conditions.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The expanded bed layer displays a state of piston flow.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The expanded bed chromatographic separation column has advantages of increasing the separation efficiency of the expanded bed.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Expanded-bed adsorption (EBA) chromatography is a convenient and effective technique for the capture of proteins directly from unclarified crude sample.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In EBA chromatography, the settled bed is first expanded by upward flow of equilibration buffer.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The crude feed, which is a mixture of soluble proteins, contaminants, cells, and cell debris, is then passed upward through the expanded bed.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Target proteins are captured on the adsorbent, while particulates and contaminants pass through.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] A change to elution buffer while maintaining upward flow results in desorption of the target protein in expanded-bed mode.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Alternatively, if the flow is reversed, the adsorbed particles will quickly settle and the proteins can be desorbed by an elution buffer.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The mode used for elution (expanded-bed versus settled-bed) depends on the characteristics of the feed.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] After elution, the adsorbent is cleaned with a predefined cleaning-in-place (CIP) solution, with cleaning followed by either column regeneration (for further use) or storage.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Reversed-phase chromatography (RPC) is any liquid chromatography procedure in which the mobile phase is significantly more polar than the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It is so named because in normal-phase liquid chromatography, the mobile phase is significantly less polar than the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Hydrophobic molecules in the mobile phase tend to adsorb to the relatively hydrophobic stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Hydrophilic molecules in the mobile phase will tend to elute first.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Separating columns typically comprise a C8 or C18 carbon-chain bonded to a silica particle substrate.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Hydrophobic Interaction Chromatography (HIC) is a purification and analytical technique that separates analytes, such as proteins, based on hydrophobic interactions between that analyte and the chromatographic matrix.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It can provide a non-denaturing orthogonal approach to reversed phase separation, preserving native structures and potentially protein activity.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In hydrophobic interaction chromatography, the matrix material is lightly substituted with hydrophobic groups.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] These groups can range from methyl, ethyl, propyl, butyl, octyl, or phenyl groups.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] At high salt concentrations, non-polar sidechains on the surface on proteins "interact" with the hydrophobic groups; that is, both types of groups are excluded by the polar solvent (hydrophobic effects are augmented by increased ionic strength).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Thus, the sample is applied to the column in a buffer which is highly polar, which drives an association of hydrophobic patches on the analyte with the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The eluent is typically an aqueous buffer with decreasing salt concentrations, increasing concentrations of detergent (which disrupts hydrophobic interactions), or changes in pH.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Of critical importance is the type of salt used, with more kosmotropic salts as defined by the Hofmeister series providing the most water structuring around the molecule and resulting hydrophobic pressure.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Ammonium sulfate is frequently used for this purpose.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The addition of organic solvents or other less polar constituents may assist in improving resolution.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In general, Hydrophobic Interaction Chromatography (HIC) is advantageous if the sample is sensitive to pH change or harsh solvents typically used in other types of chromatography but not high salt concentrations.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Commonly, it is the amount of salt in the buffer which is varied.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In 2012, Müller and Franzreb described the effects of temperature on HIC using Bovine Serum Albumin (BSA) with four different types of hydrophobic resin.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The study altered temperature as to effect the binding affinity of BSA onto the matrix.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It was concluded that cycling temperature from 40 to 10 degrees Celsius would not be adequate to effectively wash all BSA from the matrix but could be very effective if the column would only be used a few times.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Using temperature to effect change allows labs to cut costs on buying salt and saves money.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] If high salt concentrations along with temperature fluctuations want to be avoided one can use a more hydrophobic to compete with one's sample to elute it.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This so-called salt independent method of HIC showed a direct isolation of Human Immunoglobulin G (IgG) from serum with satisfactory yield and used β-cyclodextrin as a competitor to displace IgG from the matrix.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This largely opens up the possibility of using HIC with samples which are salt sensitive as we know high salt concentrations precipitate proteins.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] HILIC can be used for separation of many types of analytes, but is commonly used for metabolomics studies, where it is well suited to separate polar metabolites.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] HILIC is orthogonal to reverse-phase chromatography, and can be combined as an orthogonal approach for more comprehensive coverage.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Hydrodynamic chromatography (HDC) is derived from the observed phenomenon that large droplets move faster than small ones.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In a column, this happens because the center of mass of larger droplets is prevented from being as close to the sides of the column as smaller droplets because of their larger overall size.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Larger droplets will elute first from the middle of the column while smaller droplets stick to the sides of the column and elute last.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This form of chromatography is useful for separating analytes by molar mass (or molecular mass), size, shape, and structure when used in conjunction with light scattering detectors, viscometers, and refractometers.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The two main types of HDC are open tube and packed column.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Open tube offers rapid separation times for small particles, whereas packed column HDC can increase resolution and is better suited for particles with an average molecular mass larger than $10^{5}$ daltons.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] HDC differs from other types of chromatography because the separation only takes place in the interstitial volume, which is the volume surrounding and in between particles in a packed column.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] HDC shares the same order of elution as Size Exclusion Chromatography (SEC) but the two processes still vary in many ways.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This is largely due to SEC being a more destructive technique because of the pores in the column degrading the analyte during separation, which tends to impact the mass distribution.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] However, the main disadvantage of HDC is low resolution of analyte peaks, which makes SEC a more viable option when used with chemicals that are not easily degradable and where rapid elution is not important.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] HDC plays an especially important role in the field of microfluidics.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The first successful apparatus for HDC-on-a-chip system was proposed by Chmela, et al. in 2002.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Their design was able to achieve separations using an 80 mm long channel on the timescale of 3 minutes for particles with diameters ranging from 26 to 110 nm, but the authors expressed a need to improve the retention and dispersion parameters.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In a 2010 publication by Jellema, Markesteijn, Westerweel, and Verpoorte, implementing HDC with a recirculating bidirectional flow resulted in high resolution, size based separation with only a 3 mm long channel.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Having such a short channel and high resolution was viewed as especially impressive considering that previous studies used channels that were 80 mm in length.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] For a biological application, in 2007, Huh, et al. proposed a microfluidic sorting device based on HDC and gravity, which was useful for preventing potentially dangerous particles with diameter larger than 6 microns from entering the bloodstream when injecting contrast agents in ultrasounds.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This study also made advances for environmental sustainability in microfluidics due to the lack of outside electronics driving the flow, which came as an advantage of using a gravity based device.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In some cases, the selectivity provided by the use of one column can be insufficient to provide resolution of analytes in complex samples.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Two-dimensional chromatography aims to increase the resolution of these peaks by using a second column with different physico-chemical (chemical classification) properties.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Since the mechanism of retention on this new solid support is different from the first dimensional separation, it can be possible to separate compounds by two-dimensional chromatography that are indistinguishable by one-dimensional chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Furthermore, the separation on the second dimension occurs faster than the first dimension.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] An example of a TDC separation is where the sample is spotted at one corner of a square plate, developed, air-dried, then rotated by 90° and usually redeveloped in a second solvent system.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Two-dimensional chromatography can be applied to GC or LC separations.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The heart-cutting approach selects a specific region of interest on the first dimension for separation, and the comprehensive approach uses all analytes in the second-dimension separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The simulated moving bed (SMB) technique is a variant of high performance liquid chromatography; it is used to separate particles and/or chemical compounds that would be difficult or impossible to resolve otherwise.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This increased separation is brought about by a valve-and-column arrangement that is used to lengthen the stationary phase indefinitely.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In the moving bed technique of preparative chromatography the feed entry and the analyte recovery are simultaneous and continuous, but because of practical difficulties with a continuously moving bed, simulated moving bed technique was proposed.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In the simulated moving bed technique instead of moving the bed, the sample inlet and the analyte exit positions are moved continuously, giving the impression of a moving bed.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] True moving bed chromatography (TMBC) is only a theoretical concept.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Its simulation, SMBC is achieved by the use of a multiplicity of columns in series and a complex valve arrangement.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Pyrolysis–gas chromatography–mass spectrometry is a method of chemical analysis in which the sample is heated to decomposition to produce smaller molecules that are separated by gas chromatography and detected using mass spectrometry.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Pyrolysis is the thermal decomposition of materials in an inert atmosphere or a vacuum.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The sample is put into direct contact with a platinum wire, or placed in a quartz sample tube, and rapidly heated to 600–1000 °C.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Depending on the application even higher temperatures are used.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Three different heating techniques are used in actual pyrolyzers: Isothermal furnace, inductive heating (Curie point filament), and resistive heating using platinum filaments.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Large molecules cleave at their weakest points and produce smaller, more volatile fragments.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] These fragments can be separated by gas chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Pyrolysis GC chromatograms are typically complex because a wide range of different decomposition products is formed.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The data can either be used as fingerprints to prove material identity or the GC/MS data is used to identify individual fragments to obtain structural information.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] To increase the volatility of polar fragments, various methylating reagents can be added to a sample before pyrolysis.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Besides the usage of dedicated pyrolyzers, pyrolysis GC of solid and liquid samples can be performed directly inside Programmable Temperature Vaporizer (PTV) injectors that provide quick heating (up to 30 °C/s) and high maximum temperatures of 600–650 °C.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This is sufficient for some pyrolysis applications.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The main advantage is that no dedicated instrument has to be purchased and pyrolysis can be performed as part of routine GC analysis.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In this case, quartz GC inlet liners have to be used.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Quantitative data can be acquired, and good results of derivatization inside the PTV injector are published as well.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Fast protein liquid chromatography (FPLC), is a form of liquid chromatography that is often used to analyze or purify mixtures of proteins.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] As in other forms of chromatography, separation is possible because the different components of a mixture have different affinities for two materials, a moving fluid (the "mobile phase") and a porous solid (the stationary phase).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In FPLC the mobile phase is an aqueous solution, or "buffer".
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The buffer flow rate is controlled by a positive-displacement pump and is normally kept constant, while the composition of the buffer can be varied by drawing fluids in different proportions from two or more external reservoirs.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The stationary phase is a resin composed of beads, usually of cross-linked agarose, packed into a cylindrical glass or plastic column.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] FPLC resins are available in a wide range of bead sizes and surface ligands depending on the application.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Countercurrent chromatography (CCC) is a type of liquid-liquid chromatography, where both the stationary and mobile phases are liquids and the liquid stationary phase is held stagnant by a strong centrifugal force.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The operating principle of CCC instrument requires a column consisting of an open tube coiled around a bobbin.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The bobbin is rotated in a double-axis gyratory motion (a cardioid), which causes a variable gravity (G) field to act on the column during each rotation.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This motion causes the column to see one partitioning step per revolution and components of the sample separate in the column due to their partitioning coefficient between the two immiscible liquid phases used.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] There are many types of CCC available today.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] These include HSCCC (High Speed CCC) and HPCCC (High Performance CCC).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] HPCCC is the latest and best-performing version of the instrumentation available currently.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In the CPC (centrifugal partition chromatography or hydrostatic countercurrent chromatography) instrument, the column consists of a series of cells interconnected by ducts attached to a rotor.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This rotor rotates on its central axis creating the centrifugal field necessary to hold the stationary phase in place.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The separation process in CPC is governed solely by the partitioning of solutes between the stationary and mobile phases, which mechanism can be easily described using the partition coefficients (*KD*) of solutes.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] CPC instruments are commercially available for laboratory, pilot, and industrial-scale separations with different sizes of columns ranging from some 10 milliliters to 10 liters in volume.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In contrast to counter current chromatography (see above), periodic counter-current chromatography (PCC) uses a solid stationary phase and only a liquid mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It thus is much more similar to conventional affinity chromatography than to counter current chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] PCC uses multiple columns, which during the loading phase are connected in line.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] This mode allows for overloading the first column in this series without losing product, which already breaks through the column before the resin is fully saturated.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The breakthrough product is captured on the subsequent column(s).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In a next step the columns are disconnected from one another.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The first column is washed and eluted, while the other column(s) are still being loaded.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Once the (initially) first column is re-equilibrated, it is re-introduced to the loading stream, but as last column.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] The process then continues in a cyclic fashion.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Chiral chromatography involves the separation of stereoisomers.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] In the case of enantiomers, these have no chemical or physical differences apart from being three-dimensional mirror images.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] To enable chiral separations to take place, either the mobile phase or the stationary phase must themselves be made chiral, giving differing affinities between the analytes.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Chiral chromatography HPLC columns (with a chiral stationary phase) in both normal and reversed phase are commercially available.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Conventional chromatography are incapable of separating racemic mixtures of enantiomers.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] However, in some cases *nonracemic* mixtures of enantiomers may be separated unexpectedly by conventional liquid chromatography (e.g.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] HPLC without chiral mobile phase or stationary phase ).
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Aqueous normal-phase (ANP) chromatography is characterized by the elution behavior of classical normal phase mode (i.e. where the mobile phase is significantly less polar than the stationary phase) in which water is one of the mobile phase solvent system components.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] It is distinguished from hydrophilic interaction liquid chromatography (HILIC) in that the retention mechanism is due to adsorption rather than partitioning.
[src:chromatography-methods/chromatography] Chromatography is used in many fields including the pharmaceutical industry, the food and beverage industry, the chemical industry, forensic science, environment analysis, and hospitals.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The technique is widely applicable, as many different adsorbents (normal phase, reversed phase, or otherwise) can be used with a wide range of solvents.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The technique can be used on scales from micrograms up to kilograms.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The main advantage of column chromatography is its cost is relatively low, and the stationary phase can be replaced after use.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The latter prevents cross-contamination and stationary phase degradation due to recycling.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The mobile phase moves by gravity, compressed gas, or pressurized pumps (as in high-performance liquid chromatography).
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Before performing column chromatography, one usually performs thin-layer chromatography on a small amount of the sample first, to see how a mixture of compounds will behave when purified by column chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] This allows the experimenter to optimize the combination of mobile and stationary phases for this particular sample.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] A column is prepared by packing a solid adsorbent into a cylindrical glass or plastic tube.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The size will depend on the amount of compound being isolated.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The base of the tube contains a filter to hold the solid phase in place.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The filter is either a plug made of cotton or glass wool, or a glass frit.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] A solvent reservoir may be attached at the top of the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Two methods are generally used to prepare a column: the **dry method** and the **wet method**.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] For the dry method, the column is first filled with dry stationary phase powder, followed by the addition of mobile phase, which is flushed through the column until it is completely wet, and from this point is never allowed to run dry.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] For the wet method, a slurry is prepared of the eluent with the stationary phase powder and then carefully poured into the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The top of the silica should be flat, and the top of the silica can be protected by a layer of sand.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Eluent is slowly passed through the column to advance the organic material.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The individual components are retained by the stationary phase differently and separate from each other while they are running at different speeds through the column with the eluent.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] At the end of the column they elute one at a time.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] During the entire chromatography process the eluent is collected in a series of fractions.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Fractions can be collected automatically by means of fraction collectors.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The productivity of chromatography can be increased by running several columns at a time.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] In this case multi stream collectors are used.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The composition of the eluent flow can be monitored and each fraction is analyzed for dissolved compounds, e.g. by analytical chromatography, UV absorption spectra, or fluorescence.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Colored compounds (or fluorescent compounds with the aid of a UV lamp) can be seen through the glass wall as moving bands.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] In column chromatography, the column contains a packed column of solid particles, finely ground powders, or gels.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] This is called the *stationary phase* or *adsorbent*.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] It is most often made of silica gel or alumina.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Cellulose powder has often been used in the past.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] A wide range of stationary phases are available in order to different forms of column chromatographies: ion exchange chromatography, reversed-phase chromatography (RP), affinity chromatography or expanded bed adsorption (EBA).
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The solid phase may be microporous for an increased surface, though EBA uses a fluidized bed.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] In general, one should use much more stationary phase than the analyte mixture.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] For silica column chromatography in particular, for each gram of dry mass of the analyte mixture, there should be 20 to 100 grams of the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Using more silica would increase the resolving power of the chromatography, but also make it slower.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The *mobile phase* or *eluent* is a solvent or a mixture of solvents used to move the compounds through the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] To pick a good eluent, one run multiple small scale pretests, often using thin layer chromatography (TLC) with the same stationary phase, using solvents of different polarity, until a suitable solvent system is found.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Common mobile phase solvents, in order of increasing polarity, include hexane, dichloromethane, ethyl acetate, acetone, and methanol.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] A common solvent system is hexane:ethyl acetate mixture.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The proportions are adjusted so that the target compound has a retention factor of 0.2 - 0.3.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Contrary to common misconception, methanol alone can be used as an eluent for highly polar compounds, and does not dissolve silica gel.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] A higher flow rate eluent decreases the time required to run a column and thereby decreases diffusion, improving the resolving power.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] However, if the flow rate is too high, the analyte would fail to equilibrate between the stationary phase and mobile phase (see Van Deemter's equation).
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] To increase the flow rate of a gravity-flow column chromatography, one can increase the height of the fresh eluent column above the top of the stationary phase, or decrease the tap controls.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] It can also be increased by using a pump or by using compressed gas (e.g. air, nitrogen, or argon) to push the solvent through the column (flash column chromatography).
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The particle size of the stationary phase is generally finer in flash column chromatography than in gravity column chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] For example, one of the most widely used silica gel grades in the former technique is mesh 230 – 400 (40 – 63 μm), while the latter technique typically requires mesh 70 – 230 (63 – 200 μm) silica gel.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Column chromatography takes a long time.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Many manufacturers like Biotage, Buchi, Interchim and Teledyne Isco have developed automated flash chromatography systems that minimize human involvement in the purification process.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Such systems are typically referred to as low pressure liquid chromatography (LPLC).
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] They include components normally found on more expensive high pressure liquid chromatography (HPLC) systems such as a gradient pump, sample injection ports, a UV detector and a fraction collector to collect the eluent, but operating at a lower pressure (usually 350–525 kPa or 50.8–76.1 psi).
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Typically these automated systems can separate samples from a few milligrams up to an industrial many kilogram scale, and are cheaper and faster than doing multiple injections on preparative HPLC systems.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The resolution (or the ability to separate a mixture) of an LPLC system is lower, as the packing material in an HPLC column can be much smaller, typically only 5 micrometre.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] This increases the stationary phase surface for interactions, and gives better separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The LPLC columns are typically packed with silica of around 50 micrometres, thus reducing back pressure and resolution, but it also removes the need for expensive high pressure pumps.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Manufacturers are now starting to move into higher pressure flash chromatography systems, which operate above 1 MPa (150 psi), calling them "medium pressure liquid chromatography" (MPLC).
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Typically, column chromatography is set up with peristaltic pumps, flowing buffers and the solution sample through the top of the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The solutions and buffers pass through the column where a fraction collector at the end of the column setup collects the eluted samples.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Prior to the fraction collection, the samples that are eluted from the column pass through a detector such as a spectrophotometer or mass spectrometer so that the concentration of the separated samples in the sample solution mixture can be determined.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] For example, if you were to separate two different proteins with different binding capacities to the column from a solution sample, a good type of detector would be a spectrophotometer using a wavelength of 280 nm.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The higher the concentration of protein that passes through the eluted solution through the column, the higher the absorbance of that wavelength.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Because the column chromatography has a constant flow of eluted solution passing through the detector at varying concentrations, the detector must plot the concentration of the eluted sample over a course of time.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] This plot of sample concentration versus time is called a chromatogram.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The ultimate goal of chromatography is to separate different components from a solution mixture.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The resolution expresses the extent of separation between the components from the mixture.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The higher the resolution of the chromatogram, the better the extent of separation of the samples the column gives.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] This data is a good way of determining the column's separation properties of that particular sample.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The resolution can be calculated from the chromatogram.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The separate curves in the diagram represent different sample elution concentration profiles over time based on their affinity to the column resin.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] To calculate resolution, the retention time and curve width are required.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Retention time is the time from the start of signal detection by the detector to the peak height of the elution concentration profile of each different sample.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Curve width is the width of the concentration profile curve of the different samples in the chromatogram in units of time.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] A simplified method of calculating chromatogram resolution is to use the plate model.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The plate model assumes that the column can be divided into a certain number of sections, or plates and the mass balance can be calculated for each individual plate.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] This approach approximates a typical chromatogram curve as a Gaussian distribution curve.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] By doing this, the curve width is estimated as 4 times the standard deviation of the curve, 4σ.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The retention time is the time from the start of signal detection to the time of the peak height of the Gaussian curve.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] From the variables in the figure above, the resolution, plate number, and plate height of the column plate model can be calculated.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Plate Height $H=L/N$ , where L is the length of the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] For an adsorption column, the column resin (the stationary phase) is composed of microbeads.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Even smaller particles such as proteins, carbohydrates, metal ions, or other chemical compounds are conjugated onto the microbeads.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Each binding particle that is attached to the microbead can be assumed to bind in a 1:1 ratio with the solute sample sent through the column that needs to be purified or separated.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Using this as a basis, three different isotherms can be used to describe the binding dynamics of a column chromatography: linear, Langmuir, and Freundlich.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The linear isotherm occurs when the solute concentration needed to be purified is very small relative to the binding molecule.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] For industrial scale uses, the total binding molecules on the column resin beads must be factored in because unoccupied sites must be taken into account.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The Langmuir isotherm and Freundlich isotherm are useful in describing this equilibrium.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] is the total binding molecules on the beads.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] The Freundlich isotherm is used when the column can bind to many different samples in the solution that needs to be purified.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Because the many different samples have different binding constants to the beads, there are many different Keqs.
[src:chromatography-methods/column-chromatography] Therefore, the Langmuir isotherm is not a good model for binding in this case.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Gas chromatography is also sometimes known as **vapor-phase chromatography** (**VPC**), or **gas–liquid partition chromatography** (**GLPC**).
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] These alternative names, as well as their respective abbreviations, are frequently used in scientific literature.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Gas chromatography is the process of separating compounds in a mixture by injecting a gaseous or liquid sample into a mobile phase, typically called the carrier gas, and passing the gas through a stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The mobile phase is usually an inert gas or an unreactive gas such as helium, argon, nitrogen or hydrogen.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The stationary phase can be solid or liquid, although most GC systems today use a polymeric liquid stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The stationary phase is contained inside of a separation column.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Today, most GC columns are fused silica capillaries with an inner diameter of 100–320 micrometres (0.0039–0.0126 in) and a length of 5–60 metres (16–197 ft).
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The GC column is located inside an oven where the temperature of the gas can be controlled and the effluent coming off the column is monitored by a suitable detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] A gas chromatograph is made of a narrow tube, known as the *column*, through which the vaporized sample passes, carried along by a continuous flow of inert or nonreactive gas.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Components of the sample pass through the column at different rates, depending on their chemical and physical properties and the resulting interactions with the column lining or filling, called the *stationary phase*.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The column is typically enclosed within a temperature controlled oven.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] As the chemicals exit the end of the column, they are detected and identified electronically.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Chromatography dates to 1903 in the work of the Russian scientist, Mikhail Semenovich Tswett, who separated plant pigments via liquid column chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The invention of gas chromatography is attributed to Anthony T.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Martin at the National Institute for Medical Research in Mill Hill, London in 1951.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Their gas chromatograph used partition chromatography as the separating principle, rather than adsorption chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The popularity of gas chromatography quickly rose after the development of the flame ionization detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Martin and another one of their colleagues, Richard Synge, with whom he shared the 1952 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, had noted in an earlier paper that chromatography might also be used to separate gases.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Synge pursued other work while Martin continued his work with James.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In trying to commercialize the technology shortly after its invention, Griffin and George Ltd. based in London manufactured and sold gas chromatographs in 1954.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Other companies, such as Pye Unicam based in Cambridge and companies based in the US, would follow in 1955 and 1956.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] German physical chemist Erika Cremer in 1947 together with Austrian graduate student Fritz Prior developed what could be considered the first gas chromatograph that consisted of a carrier gas, a column packed with silica gel, and a thermal conductivity detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] They exhibited the chromatograph at ACHEMA in Frankfurt, but nobody was interested in it.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Turner with the Burrell Corporation introduced in 1943 a massive instrument that used a charcoal column and mercury vapors.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Stig Claesson of Uppsala University published in 1946 his work on a charcoal column that also used mercury.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Gerhard Hesse, while a professor at the University of Marburg/Lahn decided to test the prevailing opinion among German chemists that molecules could not be separated in a moving gas stream.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] He set up a simple glass column filled with starch and successfully separated bromine and iodine using nitrogen as the carrier gas.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] He then built a system that flowed an inert gas through a glass condenser packed with silica gel and collected the eluted fractions.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Courtenay S.G Phillips of Oxford University investigated separation in a charcoal column using a thermal conductivity detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] He consulted with Claesson and decided to use displacement as his separating principle.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] After learning about the results of James and Martin, he switched to partition chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Early gas chromatography used packed columns, made of block 1–5 m long, 1–5 mm diameter, and filled with particles.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The resolution of packed columns was improved by the invention of capillary column, in which the stationary phase is coated on the inner wall of the capillary.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The autosampler provides the means to introduce a sample automatically into the inlets.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Manual insertion of the sample is possible but is no longer common.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Automatic insertion provides better reproducibility and time-optimization.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The column inlet (or injector) provides the means to introduce a sample into a continuous flow of carrier gas.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The inlet is a piece of hardware attached to the column head.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The choice of carrier gas (mobile phase) is important.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Hydrogen has a range of flow rates that are comparable to helium in efficiency.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] However, helium may be more efficient and provide the best separation if flow rates are optimized.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Helium is non-flammable and works with a greater number of detectors and older instruments.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Therefore, helium is the most common carrier gas used.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] However, the price of helium has gone up considerably over recent years, causing an increasing number of chromatographers to switch to hydrogen gas.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Historical use, rather than rational consideration, may contribute to the continued preferential use of helium.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Commonly used detectors are the flame ionization detector (FID) and the thermal conductivity detector (TCD).
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] While TCDs are beneficial in that they are non-destructive, its low detection limit for most analytes inhibits widespread use.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] FIDs are sensitive primarily to hydrocarbons, and are more sensitive to them than TCD.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] FIDs cannot detect water or carbon dioxide which make them ideal for environmental organic analyte analysis.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] FID is two to three times more sensitive to analyte detection than TCD.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The TCD relies on the thermal conductivity of matter passing around a thin wire of tungsten-rhenium with a current traveling through it.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In this set up helium or nitrogen serve as the carrier gas because of their relatively high thermal conductivity which keep the filament cool and maintain uniform resistivity and electrical efficiency of the filament.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] When analyte molecules elute from the column, mixed with carrier gas, the thermal conductivity decreases while there is an increase in filament temperature and resistivity resulting in fluctuations in voltage ultimately causing a detector response.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Detector sensitivity is proportional to filament current while it is inversely proportional to the immediate environmental temperature of that detector as well as flow rate of the carrier gas.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In a flame ionization detector (FID), electrodes are placed adjacent to a flame fueled by hydrogen / air near the exit of the column, and when carbon containing compounds exit the column they are pyrolyzed by the flame.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] This detector works only for organic / hydrocarbon containing compounds due to the ability of the carbons to form cations and electrons upon pyrolysis which generates a current between the electrodes.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The increase in current is translated and appears as a peak in a chromatogram.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] FIDs have low detection limits (a few picograms per second) but they are unable to generate ions from carbonyl containing carbons.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] FID compatible carrier gasses include helium, hydrogen, nitrogen, and argon.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In FID, sometimes the stream is modified before entering the detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] A methanizer converts carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide into methane so that it can be detected.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] A different technology is the polyarc, by Activated Research Inc, that converts all compounds to methane.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Alkali flame detector (AFD) or alkali flame ionization detector (AFID) has high sensitivity to nitrogen and phosphorus, similar to NPD.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] However, the alkaline metal ions are supplied with the hydrogen gas, rather than a bead above the flame.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] For this reason AFD does not suffer the "fatigue" of the NPD, but provides a constant sensitivity over long period of time.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In addition, when alkali ions are not added to the flame, AFD operates like a standard FID.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] A catalytic combustion detector (CCD) measures combustible hydrocarbons and hydrogen.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Discharge ionization detector (DID) uses a high-voltage electric discharge to produce ions.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Flame photometric detector (FPD) uses a photomultiplier tube to detect spectral lines of the compounds as they are burned in a flame.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Compounds eluting off the column are carried into a hydrogen fueled flame which excites specific elements in the molecules, and the excited elements (P,S, Halogens, Some Metals) emit light of specific characteristic wavelengths.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The emitted light is filtered and detected by a photomultiplier tube.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In particular, phosphorus emission is around 510–536 nm and sulfur emission is at 394 nm.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] With an atomic emission detector (AED), a sample eluting from a column enters a chamber which is energized by microwaves that induce a plasma.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The plasma causes the analyte sample to decompose and certain elements generate an atomic emission spectra.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The atomic emission spectra is diffracted by a diffraction grating and detected by a series of photomultiplier tubes or photo diodes.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Electron capture detector (ECD) uses a radioactive beta particle (electron) source to measure the degree of electron capture.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] ECD are used for the detection of molecules containing electronegative / withdrawing elements and functional groups like halogens, carbonyl, nitriles, nitro groups, and organometalics.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In this type of detector either nitrogen or 5% methane in argon is used as the mobile phase carrier gas.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The carrier gas passes between two electrodes placed at the end of the column, and adjacent to the cathode (negative electrode) resides a radioactive foil such as 63Ni.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The radioactive foil emits a beta particle (electron) which collides with and ionizes the carrier gas to generate more ions resulting in a current.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] When analyte molecules with electronegative / withdrawing elements or functional groups electrons are captured which results in a decrease in current generating a detector response.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Nitrogen–phosphorus detector (NPD), a form of thermionic detector where nitrogen and phosphorus alter the work function on a specially coated bead and a resulting current is measured.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Dry electrolytic conductivity detector (DELCD) uses an air phase and high temperature (v.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Coulsen) to measure chlorinated compounds.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Mass spectrometer (MS), also called GC-MS; highly effective and sensitive, even in a small quantity of sample.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] This detector can be used to identify the analytes in chromatograms by their mass spectrum.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Some GC-MS are connected to an NMR spectrometer which acts as a backup detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Some GC-MS-NMR are connected to an infrared spectrophotometer which acts as a backup detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] This combination is known as GC-MS-NMR-IR.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] It must, however, be stressed this is very rare as most analyses needed can be concluded via purely GC-MS.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Vacuum ultraviolet (VUV) represents the most recent development in gas chromatography detectors.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Most chemical species absorb and have unique gas phase absorption cross sections in the approximately 120–240 nm VUV wavelength range monitored.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Where absorption cross sections are known for analytes, the VUV detector is capable of absolute determination (without calibration) of the number of molecules present in the flow cell in the absence of chemical interferences.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Olfactometric detector, also called GC-O, uses a human assessor to analyse the odour activity of compounds.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] With an odour port or a sniffing port, the quality of the odour, the intensity of the odour and the duration of the odour activity of a compound can be assessed.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Other detectors include the Hall electrolytic conductivity detector (ElCD), helium ionization detector (HID), infrared detector (IRD), photo-ionization detector (PID), pulsed discharge ionization detector (PDD), and thermionic ionization detector (TID).
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The method is the collection of conditions in which the GC operates for a given analysis.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Method development is the process of determining what conditions are adequate and/or ideal for the analysis required.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Depending on the detector(s) (see below) installed on the GC, there may be a number of detector conditions that can also be varied.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Some GCs also include valves which can change the route of sample and carrier flow.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The timing of the opening and closing of these valves can be important to method development.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Typical carrier gases include helium, nitrogen, argon, and hydrogen.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Which gas to use is usually determined by the detector being used, for example, a DID requires helium as the carrier gas.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] When analyzing gas samples the carrier is also selected based on the sample's matrix, for example, when analyzing a mixture in argon, an argon carrier is preferred because the argon in the sample does not show up on the chromatogram.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Safety and availability can also influence carrier selection.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The purity of the carrier gas is also frequently determined by the detector, though the level of sensitivity needed can also play a significant role.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Typically, purities of 99.995% or higher are used.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The most common purity grades required by modern instruments for the majority of sensitivities are 5.0 grades, or 99.999% pure meaning that there is a total of 10 ppm of impurities in the carrier gas that could affect the results.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The highest purity grades in common use are 6.0 grades, but the need for detection at very low levels in some forensic and environmental applications has driven the need for carrier gases at 7.0 grade purity and these are now commercially available.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Trade names for typical purities include "Zero Grade", "Ultra-High Purity (UHP) Grade", "4.5 Grade" and "5.0 Grade".
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The carrier gas linear velocity affects the analysis in the same way that temperature does (see above).
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The higher the linear velocity the faster the analysis, but the lower the separation between analytes.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Selecting the linear velocity is therefore the same compromise between the level of separation and length of analysis as selecting the column temperature.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The linear velocity will be implemented by means of the carrier gas flow rate, with regards to the inner diameter of the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] With GCs made before the 1990s, carrier flow rate was controlled indirectly by controlling the carrier inlet pressure, or "column head pressure".
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The actual flow rate was measured at the outlet of the column or the detector with an electronic flow meter, or a bubble flow meter, and could be an involved, time consuming, and frustrating process.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] It was not possible to vary the pressure setting during the run, and thus the flow was essentially constant during the analysis.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The relation between flow rate and inlet pressure is calculated with Poiseuille's equation for compressible fluids.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Many modern GCs, however, electronically measure the flow rate, and electronically control the carrier gas pressure to set the flow rate.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Consequently, carrier pressures and flow rates can be adjusted during the run, creating pressure/flow programs similar to temperature programs.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The polarity of the solute is crucial for the choice of stationary compound, which in an optimal case would have a similar polarity as the solute.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Common stationary phases in open tubular columns are cyanopropylphenyl dimethyl polysiloxane, carbowax polyethyleneglycol, biscyanopropyl cyanopropylphenyl polysiloxane and diphenyl dimethyl polysiloxane.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] For packed columns more options are available.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The choice of inlet type and injection technique depends on if the sample is in liquid, gas, adsorbed, or solid form, and on whether a solvent matrix is present that has to be vaporized.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The real chromatographic analysis starts with the introduction of the sample onto the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The development of capillary gas chromatography resulted in many practical problems with the injection technique.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The technique of on-column injection, often used with packed columns, is usually not possible with capillary columns.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In the injection system in the capillary gas chromatograph the amount injected should not overload the column and the width of the injected plug should be small compared to the spreading due to the chromatographic process.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Failure to comply with this latter requirement will reduce the separation capability of the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] As a general rule, the volume injected, Vinj, and the volume of the detector cell, Vdet, should be about 1/10 of the volume occupied by the portion of sample containing the molecules of interest (analytes) when they exit the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] However, there are a number of problems inherent in the use of syringes for injection.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Even the best syringes claim an accuracy of only 3%, and in unskilled hands, errors are much larger.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The needle may cut small pieces of rubber from the septum as it injects sample through it.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] These can block the needle and prevent the syringe filling the next time it is used.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] It may not be obvious that this has happened.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] A fraction of the sample may get trapped in the rubber, to be released during subsequent injections.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] This can give rise to ghost peaks in the chromatogram.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] There may be selective loss of the more volatile components of the sample by evaporation from the tip of the needle.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The choice of column depends on the sample and the active measured.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The main chemical attribute regarded when choosing a column is the polarity of the mixture, but functional groups can play a large part in column selection.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The polarity of the sample must closely match the polarity of the column stationary phase to increase resolution and separation while reducing run time.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The separation and run time also depends on the film thickness (of the stationary phase), the column diameter and the column length.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The column(s) in a GC are contained in an oven, the temperature of which is precisely controlled electronically.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] (When discussing the "temperature of the column", an analyst is technically referring to the temperature of the column oven.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The rate at which a sample passes through the column is directly proportional to the temperature of the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The higher the column temperature, the faster the sample moves through the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] However, the faster a sample moves through the column, the less it interacts with the stationary phase, and the less the analytes are separated.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In general, the column temperature is selected to compromise between the length of the analysis and the level of separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] A method which holds the column at the same temperature for the entire analysis is called "isothermal".
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Most methods, however, increase the column temperature during the analysis, the initial temperature, rate of temperature increase (the temperature "ramp"), and final temperature are called the temperature program.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] A temperature program allows analytes that elute early in the analysis to separate adequately, while shortening the time it takes for late-eluting analytes to pass through the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Generally, chromatographic data is presented as a graph of detector response (y-axis) against retention time (x-axis), which is called a chromatogram.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] This provides a spectrum of peaks for a sample representing the analytes present in a sample eluting from the column at different times.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Retention time can be used to identify analytes if the method conditions are constant.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Also, the pattern of peaks will be constant for a sample under constant conditions and can identify complex mixtures of analytes.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] However, in most modern applications, the GC is connected to a mass spectrometer or similar detector that is capable of identifying the analytes represented by the peaks.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The area under a peak is proportional to the amount of analyte present in the chromatogram.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] By calculating the area of the peak using the mathematical function of integration, the concentration of an analyte in the original sample can be determined.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Concentration can be calculated using a calibration curve created by finding the response for a series of concentrations of analyte, or by determining the relative response factor of an analyte.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In most modern GC-MS systems, computer software is used to draw and integrate peaks, and match MS spectra to library spectra.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In general, substances that vaporize below 300 °C (and therefore are stable up to that temperature) can be measured quantitatively.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The samples are also required to be salt-free; they should not contain ions.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Very minute amounts of a substance can be measured, but it is often required that the sample must be measured in comparison to a sample containing the pure, suspected substance known as a reference standard.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Various temperature programs can be used to make the readings more meaningful; for example to differentiate between substances that behave similarly during the GC process.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Professionals working with GC analyze the content of a chemical product, for example in assuring the quality of products in the chemical industry; or measuring chemicals in soil, air or water, such as soil gases.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] GC is very accurate if used properly and can measure picomoles of a substance in a 1 ml liquid sample, or parts-per-billion concentrations in gaseous samples.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In practical courses at colleges, students sometimes get acquainted to the GC by studying the contents of lavender oil or measuring the ethylene that is secreted by *Nicotiana benthamiana* plants after artificially injuring their leaves.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] These GC analyse hydrocarbons (C2-C40+).
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] In a typical experiment, a packed column is used to separate the light gases, which are then detected with a TCD.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The hydrocarbons are separated using a capillary column and detected with a FID.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] For this reason, dual TCD instruments used with a separate channel for hydrogen that uses nitrogen as a carrier are common.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Argon is often used when analysing gas phase chemistry reactions such as F-T synthesis so that a single carrier gas can be used rather than two separate ones.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] The sensitivity is reduced, but this is a trade off for simplicity in the gas supply.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Gas chromatography is used extensively in forensic science.
[src:chromatography-methods/gas-chromatography] Disciplines as diverse as solid drug dose (pre-consumption form) identification and quantification, arson investigation, paint chip analysis, and toxicology cases, employ GC to identify and quantify various biological specimens and crime-scene evidence.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] HPLC is essentially a pressurized form of column chromatography, which uses pressurized pumps instead of the force of gravity, and thinner and longer columns with smaller adsorbent particles.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] These increases its analytic resolution.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] High pressure pumps force mixtures of various solvents (the mobile phase, *e.g.*, water, buffers, acetonitrile and/or methanol) to flow through a sample mixture and pick up analytes, delivering it into a cylinder (the chromatography column).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The column is filled with solid particles made of adsorbent material (the stationary phase).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The particles are usually made of silica, polymers, and 1.5–50 μm in diameter.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Elution occurs as the mobile phase passes through the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Each component in the sample interacts differently with the adsorbent material and the solvents, so their rates of elution are different.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] These different rates lead to analytical separation of the species in the fluid that flows out of the column (the eluate).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The eluate enters a specific chromatography detector such as UV detectors, which produces a graph (the chromatogram).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] A chromatogram is a graph of detector signal intensity versus time or the volume of the mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] If the analytes are well-separated, then the chromatogram would show well-separated peaks, one per analyte.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Each analyte appears in its respective time (retention time) having area proportional to its amount.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Chromatography can be described as a mass transfer process involving adsorption and/or partition.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] As mentioned, HPLC relies on pumps to pass a pressurized liquid and a sample mixture through a column filled with the adsorbent (the active component of the column).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Some analytes may strongly attach to the adsorbent rather than the eluent, while other analytes may do the opposite.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] That is, the analytes may have different partition coefficients, leading to the separation of the analytes.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The interaction between the analyte, the solid phase, and the liquid phase, are physical or chemically reversible, usually a combination of non-covalent interactions.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The liquid chromatograph is complex and has sophisticated and delicate technology.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In order to properly operate the system, there should be a minimum basis for understanding of how the device performs the data processing to avoid incorrect data and distorted results.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] HPLC is distinguished from traditional ("low pressure") liquid chromatography because operational pressures are significantly higher (around 50–1400 bar), while ordinary liquid chromatography typically relies on the force of gravity to pass the mobile phase through the packed column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Due to the small sample amount separated in analytical HPLC, typical column dimensions are 2.1–4.6 mm diameter, and 30–250 mm length.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Also HPLC columns are made with smaller adsorbent particles (1.5–50 μm in average particle size).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This gives HPLC superior resolving power (the ability to distinguish between compounds) when separating mixtures in a shorter period of time, which makes it a popular chromatographic technique.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The schematic of an HPLC instrument typically includes solvents' reservoirs, one or more pumps, a solvent-degasser, a sampler, a column, and a detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The pumps deliver the desired flow and composition of the mobile phase through the stationary phase inside the column, then directly into a flow-cell inside the detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The detector generates a signal proportional to the amount of sample component emerging from the column, hence allowing for quantitative analysis of the sample components.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The detector also marks the time of emergence, the retention time, which serves for initial identification of the component.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] More advanced detectors, provide also additional information, specific to the analyte's characteristics, such as UV-VIS spectrum or mass spectrum, which can provide insight on its structural features.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] These detectors are in common use, such as UV/Vis, photodiode array (PDA) / diode array detector and mass spectrometry detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] A digital microprocessor and user software control the HPLC instrument and provide data analysis.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Some models of mechanical pumps in an HPLC instrument can mix multiple solvents together at a ratios changing in time, generating a composition gradient in the mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Newer HPLC instruments have a column oven that allows for adjusting the temperature at which the separation is performed.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The sample mixture to be separated and analyzed is introduced, in a discrete small volume (typically microliters), into the stream of mobile phase percolating through the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The components of the sample move through the column, each at a different velocity, which are a function of specific physical interactions with the adsorbent, the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The velocity of each component depends on its chemical nature, on the nature of the stationary phase (inside the column) and on the composition of the mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The time at which a specific analyte elutes (emerges from the column) is called its retention time.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The retention time, measured under particular conditions, is an identifying characteristic of a given analyte.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Many different types of columns are available, filled with adsorbents varying in particle size, porosity, and surface chemistry.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The use of smaller particle size packing materials requires the use of higher operational pressure ("backpressure") and typically improves chromatographic resolution (the degree of peak separation between consecutive analytes emerging from the column).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Sorbent particles may be ionic, hydrophobic or polar in nature.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The most common mode of liquid chromatography is reversed phase, whereby the mobile phases used include any miscible combination of water or buffers with various organic solvents (the most common are acetonitrile and methanol).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Some HPLC techniques use water-free mobile phases (see normal-phase chromatography below).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The aqueous component of the mobile phase may contain acids (such as formic, phosphoric or trifluoroacetic acid) or salts to assist in the separation of the sample components.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The composition of the mobile phase may be kept constant ("isocratic elution mode") or varied ("gradient elution mode") during the chromatographic analysis.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Isocratic elution is typically effective in the separation of simple mixtures.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Gradient elution is required for complex mixtures, with varying interactions with the stationary and mobile phases.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This is the reason why in gradient elution the composition of the mobile phase is varied typically from low to high eluting strength.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The eluting strength of the mobile phase is reflected by analyte retention times, as the high eluting strength speeds up the elution (resulting in shortening of retention times).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] For example, a typical gradient profile in reversed phase chromatography might start at 5% acetonitrile (in water or aqueous buffer) and progress linearly to 95% acetonitrile over 5–25 minutes.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Periods of constant mobile phase composition (plateau) may be also part of a gradient profile.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] For example, the mobile phase composition may be kept constant at 5% acetonitrile for 1–3 min, followed by a linear change up to 95% acetonitrile.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The chosen composition of the mobile phase depends on the intensity of interactions between various sample components ("analytes") and stationary phase (*e.g.*, hydrophobic interactions in reversed-phase HPLC).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Depending on their affinity for the stationary and mobile phases, analytes partition between the two during the separation process taking place in the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This partitioning process is similar to that which occurs during a liquid–liquid extraction but is continuous, not step-wise.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In the example using a water/acetonitrile gradient, the more hydrophobic components will elute (come off the column) later, then, once the mobile phase gets richer in acetonitrile (*i.e.*, in a mobile phase becomes higher eluting solution), their elution speeds up.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The choice of mobile phase components, additives (such as salts or acids) and gradient conditions depends on the nature of the column and sample components.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Often a series of trial runs is performed with the sample in order to find the HPLC method which gives adequate separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Prior to HPLC, scientists used benchtop column liquid chromatographic techniques.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Liquid chromatographic systems were largely inefficient due to the flow rate of solvents being dependent on gravity.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Separations took many hours, and sometimes days to complete.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Gas chromatography (GC) at the time was more powerful than liquid chromatography (LC), however, it was obvious that gas phase separation and analysis of very polar high molecular weight biopolymers was impossible.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] GC was ineffective for many life science and health applications for biomolecules, because they are mostly non-volatile and thermally unstable at the high temperatures of GC.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] As a result, alternative methods were hypothesized which would soon result in the development of HPLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] These predictions underwent extensive experimentation and refinement throughout the 60s into the 70s until these very days.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Early developmental research began to improve LC particles, for example the historic Zipax, a superficially porous particle.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The 1970s brought about many developments in hardware and instrumentation.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Researchers began using pumps and injectors to make a rudimentary design of an HPLC system.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Gas amplifier pumps were ideal because they operated at constant pressure and did not require leak-free seals or check valves for steady flow and good quantitation.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Hardware milestones were made at Dupont IPD (Industrial Polymers Division) such as a low-dwell-volume gradient device being utilized as well as replacing the septum injector with a loop injection valve.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] While instrumentation developments were important, the history of HPLC is primarily about the history and evolution of particle technology.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] After the introduction of porous layer particles, there has been a steady trend to reduced particle size to improve efficiency.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] However, by decreasing particle size, new problems arose.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The practical disadvantages stem from the excessive pressure drop needed to force mobile fluid through the column and the difficulty of preparing a uniform packing of extremely fine materials.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Every time particle size is reduced significantly, another round of instrument development usually must occur to handle the pressure.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Partition chromatography was one of the first kinds of chromatography that chemists developed, and is barely used these days.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The partition coefficient principle has been applied in paper chromatography, thin layer chromatography, gas phase and liquid–liquid separation applications.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The 1952 Nobel Prize in chemistry was earned by Archer John Porter Martin and Richard Laurence Millington Synge for their development of the technique, which was used for their separation of amino acids.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Partition chromatography uses a retained solvent, on the surface or within the grains or fibers of an "inert" solid supporting matrix as with paper chromatography; or takes advantage of some coulombic and/or hydrogen donor interaction with the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Analyte molecules partition between a liquid stationary phase and the eluent.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Just as in hydrophilic interaction chromatography (HILIC; a sub-technique within HPLC), this method separates analytes based on differences in their polarity.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] HILIC most often uses a bonded polar stationary phase and a mobile phase made primarily of acetonitrile with water as the strong component.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Partition HPLC has been used historically on unbonded silica or alumina supports.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Each works effectively for separating analytes by relative polar differences.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] HILIC bonded phases have the advantage of separating acidic, basic and neutral solutes in a single chromatographic run.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The polar analytes diffuse into a stationary water layer associated with the polar stationary phase and are thus retained.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The stronger the interactions between the polar analyte and the polar stationary phase (relative to the mobile phase) the longer the elution time.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The interaction strength depends on the functional groups part of the analyte molecular structure, with more polarized groups (*e.g.*, hydroxyl-) and groups capable of hydrogen bonding inducing more retention.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Coulombic (electrostatic) interactions can also increase retention.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Use of more polar solvents in the mobile phase will decrease the retention time of the analytes, whereas more hydrophobic solvents tend to increase retention times.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Normal–phase chromatography was one of the first kinds of HPLC that chemists developed, but has decreased in use over the last decades.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] NP-HPLC uses a non-polar, non-aqueous mobile phase (*e.g.*, chloroform), and works effectively for separating analytes readily soluble in non-polar solvents.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The analyte associates with and is retained by the polar stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Adsorption strengths increase with increased analyte polarity.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The interaction strength depends not only on the functional groups present in the structure of the analyte molecule, but also on steric factors.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The effect of steric hindrance on interaction strength allows this method to resolve (separate) structural isomers.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The use of more polar solvents in the mobile phase will decrease the retention time of analytes, whereas more hydrophobic solvents tend to induce slower elution (increased retention times).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Very polar solvents such as traces of water in the mobile phase tend to adsorb to the solid surface of the stationary phase forming a stationary bound (water) layer which is considered to play an active role in retention.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This behavior is somewhat peculiar to normal phase chromatography because it is governed almost exclusively by an adsorptive mechanism (*i.e.*, analytes interact with a solid surface rather than with the solvated layer of a ligand attached to the sorbent surface; see also reversed-phase HPLC below).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Adsorption chromatography is still somewhat used for structural isomer separations in both column and thin-layer chromatography formats on activated (dried) silica or alumina supports.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Partition- and NP-HPLC fell out of favor in the 1970s with the development of reversed-phase HPLC because of poor reproducibility of retention times due to the presence of a water or protic organic solvent layer on the surface of the silica or alumina chromatographic media.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This layer changes with any changes in the composition of the mobile phase (*e.g.*, moisture level) causing drifting retention times.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Recently, partition chromatography has become popular again with the development of Hilic bonded phases which demonstrate improved reproducibility, and due to a better understanding of the range of usefulness of the technique.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The use of displacement chromatography is rather limited, and is mostly used for preparative chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The basic principle is based on a molecule with a high affinity for the chromatography matrix (the displacer) which is used to compete effectively for binding sites, and thus displace all molecules with lesser affinities.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Wide separation of peaks, preferably to baseline, is desired in order to achieve maximum purification.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Because the process takes advantage of the nonlinearity of the isotherms, a larger column feed can be separated on a given column with the purified components recovered at significantly higher concentration.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Reversed-phase HPLC (RP-HPLC) is the most widespread mode of chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] It has a non-polar stationary phase and an aqueous, moderately polar mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] RP-HPLC is so commonly used among the biologists and life science users, that it is often referred to as simply "HPLC".
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The pharmaceutical industry also regularly employs RP-HPLC to qualify drugs before their release.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In the reversed phase methods, the substances are retained in the system the more hydrophobic they are.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] For the retention of organic materials, the stationary phases, are consisted mainly of porous granules of silica gel packed in the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In shape, they are usually spheres of varying diameters (sub-2, 3, 5, 7, 10 μm), varying pore diameters (60, 100, 150, 300 Å).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] On their surface are chemically bonded straight chain alkyl ligands, such as C3, C4, C8, C18.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The number counts the carbon atoms in a ligand.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The longer the hydrocarbon ligand on the stationary phase, the longer the sample components can be retained.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Most of the current methods of separation of biomedical materials use C18 stationary phase, sometimes called by a trade names such as ODS (octadecylsilane) or RP-18 (Reversed Phase 18).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] To make such stationary phases, one treat the surface of silica gel particles with RMe2SiCl, where R is a straight chain alkyl group such as C18H37 or C8H17.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] To separate aromatic compounds, or in general compounds with many pi bonds, the stationary phase can have phenyl surface ligands.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] At pH < 2, the bond between the ligand and the silica gel may dissolve.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] When solutions at extreme pH are needed, the stationary phase can be made of silica polymerized with organic substances, or hydrophobic organic polymers.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] With such stationary phases, retention time is longer for nonpolar molecules, whereas polar molecules elute more readily (emerge early in the analysis).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] A chromatographer can increase retention times by adding more water to the mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Since water is highly polar, it makes the nonpolar analyte interact more strongly with nonpolar stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Similarly, an investigator can decrease retention time by adding more organic nonpolar solvent to the mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] RP-HPLC operates on the principle of hydrophobic interactions, which originates from the high symmetry in the dipolar water structure and plays the most important role in all processes in life science.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] RP-HPLC allows the measurement of these interactive forces.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The binding of the analyte to the stationary phase is proportional to the contact surface area around the non-polar segment of the analyte molecule upon association with the ligand on the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This solvophobic effect is dominated by the force of water for "cavity-reduction" around the analyte and the C18-chain versus the complex of both.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The energy released in this process is proportional to the surface tension of the eluent (water: 7.3×10−6 J/cm2, methanol: 2.2×10−6 J/cm2) and to the hydrophobic surface of the analyte and the ligand respectively.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The retention can be decreased by adding a less polar solvent (methanol, acetonitrile) into the mobile phase to reduce the surface tension of water.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Gradient elution uses this effect by automatically reducing the polarity and the surface tension of the aqueous mobile phase during the course of the analysis.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Structural properties of the analyte molecule can play an important role in its retention characteristics.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In theory, an analyte with a larger hydrophobic surface area (C–H, C–C, and generally non-polar atomic bonds, such as S-S and others) can be retained longer as it does not interact with the water structure.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] On the other hand, analytes with higher polar surface area (as a result of the presence of polar groups, such as -OH, -NH2, COO− or -NH3+ in their structure) are less retained, as they are better integrated into water.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The interactions with the stationary phase can also affected by steric effects, or exclusion effects, whereby a component of very large molecule may have only restricted access to the pores of the stationary phase, where the interactions with surface ligands (alkyl chains) take place.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Such surface hindrance typically results in less retention.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Retention time increases with more hydrophobic (non-polar) surface area of the molecules.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] For example, branched chain compounds can elute more rapidly than their corresponding linear isomers, because their overall surface area is lower.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Similarly, organic compounds with single C–C bonds frequently elute later than those with a C=C or C≡C, since the double or triple bond makes the molecule more compact than a single bond.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Another important factor is the mobile phase pH since it can change the hydrophobic character of the ionizable analyte.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] For this reason most methods use a buffering agent, such as sodium phosphate, to control the pH.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The effects of controlling for pH and buffers vary by application, but generally improve chromatographic resolution for analytes that are ionizable.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] If mass spectrometry is used to analyze the eluate, then a volatile organic acid often added to the eluent such as acetic acid or formic acid.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Ammonium formate is commonly added to improve detection of certain analytes by the formation of analyte-ammonium adducts, which are more volatile than the analytes themselves.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Trifluoroacetic acid (TFA) as additive to the mobile phase is widely used for complex mixtures of biomedical samples, mostly peptides and proteins, using mostly UV based detectors.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] TFA also increases retention of analytes such as carboxylic acids, in applications utilizing other detectors (such as UV-VIS), as it is a fairly strong organic acid.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] However, they are rarely used in mass spectrometry methods, due to residues it can leave in the detector and solvent delivery system, which interfere with the analysis and detection.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The silica particles in reverse-phase are less likely to be damaged compared to silica particles in normal-phase, since they are shielded by surface-bonded hydrophobic ligands.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] However, most reversed phase columns consist of alkyl derivatized silica particles, and are prone to hydrolysis of the silica at acidic conditions (pH < 2).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Also, silica itself dissolves at alkaline onditions (pH > 8).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] There are selected brands of hybrid or enforced silica based particles of RP columns which can be used at extreme pH conditions.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Highly acidic conditions might also corrode the metallic parts of the HPLC equipment.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] As a rule, in most cases RP-HPLC columns should be flushed with clean solvent after use to remove residual acids or buffers, and stored in an appropriate composition of solvent.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Some biomedical applications require non metallic environment for the optimal separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] For such sensitive cases there is a test for the metal content of a column is to inject a sample which is a mixture of 2,2'- and 4,4'-bipyridine.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Because the 2,2'-bipy can chelate the metal, the shape of the peak for the 2,2'-bipy will be distorted (tailed) when metal ions are present on the surface of the silica...
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] **Gel filtration chromatography (GFC)**—separation of water-soluble biopolymers (typically proteins), using primarily aqueous solvents.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The separation principle in SEC is based on the fully, or partially penetrating of the high molecular weight substances of the sample into the porous stationary-phase particles during their transport through column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The mobile-phase eluent is selected in such a way that it totally prevents interactions with the stationary phase's surface.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Under these conditions, the smaller the size of the molecule, the more it is able to penetrate inside the pore space and the movement through the column takes longer.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] On the other hand, the bigger the molecular size, the higher the probability the molecule will not fully penetrate the pores of the stationary phase, and even travel around them, thus, will be eluted earlier.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The molecules are separated in order of decreasing molecular weight, with the largest molecules eluting from the column first and smaller molecules eluting later.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Molecules larger than the pore size do not enter the pores at all, and elute together as the first peak in the chromatogram and this is called total exclusion volume which defines the exclusion limit for a particular column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Small molecules will permeate fully through the pores of the stationary phase particles and will be eluted last, marking the end of the chromatogram, and may appear as a total penetration marker.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In biomedical sciences it is generally considered as a low resolution chromatography and thus it is often reserved for the final, "polishing" step of the purification.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] It is also useful for determining the tertiary structure and quaternary structure of purified proteins.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] SEC is used primarily for the analysis of large molecules such as proteins or polymers.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] SEC works also in a preparative way by trapping the smaller molecules in the pores of a particles.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The larger molecules simply pass by the pores as they are too large to enter the pores.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Larger molecules therefore flow through the column quicker than smaller molecules: that is, the smaller the molecule, the longer the retention time.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This technique is widely used for the molecular weight determination of polysaccharides.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] SEC is the official technique of the European Pharmacopoeia for the molecular weight comparison of different commercially available low-molecular weight heparins.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In IEC, there are electrically charged sites bound to the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Solute ions charged the same as the ions on the column are repulsed and elute without retention, while solute ions charged oppositely to the charged sites of the column are retained on it.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In general, ions of higher charge and smaller radius are more strongly retained.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Solute ions that are retained on the column can be eluted from it by changing the mobile phase composition, such as increasing its salt concentration and pH, or increasing the stationary phase temperature, etc.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Types of ion exchangers include polystyrene resins, cellulose and dextran ion exchangers (gels), and controlled-pore glass or porous silica gel.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Polystyrene resins allow cross linkage, which increases the stability of the chain.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Higher cross linkage reduces swerving, which increases the equilibration time and ultimately improves selectivity.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Cellulose and dextran ion exchangers possess larger pore sizes and low charge densities making them suitable for protein separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] An increase in counter ion (with respect to the functional groups in resins) concentration reduces the retention time, as it creates a strong competition with the solute ions.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] A decrease in pH reduces the retention time in cation exchange while an increase in pH reduces the retention time in anion exchange.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] By lowering the pH of the solvent in a cation exchange column, for instance, more hydrogen ions are available to compete for positions on the anionic stationary phase, thereby eluting weakly bound cations.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This form of chromatography is widely used in the following applications: water purification, preconcentration of trace components, ligand-exchange chromatography, ion-exchange chromatography of proteins, high-pH anion-exchange chromatography of carbohydrates and oligosaccharides, and others.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] High performance affinity chromatography (HPAC) works by passing a sample solution through a column packed with a stationary phase that contains an immobilized biologically active ligand.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The ligand is in fact a substrate that has a specific binding affinity for the target molecule in the sample solution.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The target molecule binds to the ligand, while the other molecules in the sample solution pass through the column, having little or no retention.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The target molecule is then eluted from the column using a suitable elution buffer.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This chromatographic process relies on the capability of the bonded active substances to form stable, specific, and reversible complexes thanks to their biological recognition of certain specific sample components.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The formation of these complexes involves the participation of common molecular forces such as the Van der Waals interaction, electrostatic interaction, dipole-dipole interaction, hydrophobic interaction, and the hydrogen bond.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] An efficient, specific bond is formed by a simultaneous and concerted action of several of these forces in the complementary binding sites.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] During the separation, the mobile phase composition may stay the same, or change.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] If it stays the same, the process is termed *isocratic* (meaning *constant composition*).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The word was coined by Csaba Horvath who was one of the pioneers of HPLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] If it changes, then the process is termed a *gradient elution*.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] For example, a gradient can start at 10% methanol in water, and end at 90% methanol in water after 20 minutes.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The two components of the mobile phase are typically termed "A" and "B"; *A* is the "weak" solvent which allows the solute to elute only slowly, while *B* is the "strong" solvent which rapidly elutes the solutes from the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In reversed-phase chromatography, solvent *A* is often water or an aqueous buffer, while *B* is an organic solvent miscible with water, such as acetonitrile, methanol, THF, or isopropanol.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In isocratic elution, peak width increases with retention time linearly according to the equation for N, the number of theoretical plates.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This can be a major disadvantage when analyzing a sample that contains analytes with a wide range of retention factors.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Using a weaker mobile phase, the runtime is lengthened and results in slowly eluting peaks to be broad, leading to reduced sensitivity.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] A stronger mobile phase would improve issues of runtime and broadening of later peaks but results in diminished peak separation, especially for quickly eluting analytes which may have insufficient time to fully resolve.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This issue is addressed through the changing mobile phase composition of gradient elution.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This also improves the peak shape for tailed peaks, as the increasing concentration of the organic eluent pushes the tailing part of a peak forward.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This also increases the peak height (the peak looks "sharper"), which is important in trace analysis.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The gradient program may include sudden "step" increases in the percentage of the organic component, or different slopes at different times – all according to the desire for optimum separation in minimum time.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In isocratic elution, the retention order does not change if the column dimensions (length and inner diameter) change – that is, the peaks elute in the same order.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The driving force in reversed phase chromatography originates in the high order of the water structure.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The theory of general chromatography applies to HPLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This theory is the basis for **system-suitability tests** of the United States Pharmacopoeia, which are a set of quantitative criteria for how suitable a HPLC system is to the required analysis at any step of it.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The ratio between the retention factors, k', of every two adjacent peaks in the chromatogram is used in the evaluation of the degree of separation between them, and is called **selectivity factor**, α, as shown in the Performance Criteria graph.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The plate count N as a criterion for system efficiency was developed for isocratic conditions, i.e., a constant mobile phase composition throughout the run.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In gradient conditions, where the mobile phase changes with time during the chromatographic run, it is more appropriate to use the parameter ***peak capacity* *P*c** as a measure for the system efficiency.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The definition of *peak capacity* in chromatography is the number of peaks that can be separated within a retention window for a specific pre-defined resolution factor, usually ~1.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] It could also be envisioned as the runtime measured in number of peaks' average widths.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The equation is shown in the Figure of the performance criteria.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In this equation tg is the gradient time and w(ave) is the average peaks width at the base.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The parameters are largely derived from two sets of chromatographic theory: plate theory (as part of partition chromatography), and the rate theory of chromatography / van Deemter equation.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Of course, they can be put in practice through analysis of HPLC chromatograms, although rate theory is considered the more accurate theory.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] They are analogous to the calculation of retention factor for a paper chromatography separation, but describes how well HPLC separates a mixture into two or more components that are detected as peaks (bands) on a chromatogram.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The HPLC parameters are the: efficiency factor(*N*), the retention factor (kappa prime), and the separation factor (alpha).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Together the factors are variables in a resolution equation, which describes how well two components' peaks separated or overlapped each other.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] These parameters are mostly only used for describing HPLC reversed phase and HPLC normal phase separations, since those separations tend to be more subtle than other HPLC modes (*e.g.*, ion exchange and size exclusion).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Void volume is the amount of space in a column that is occupied by solvent.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] It is the space within the column that is outside of the column's internal packing material.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Void volume is measured on a chromatogram as the first component peak detected, which is usually the solvent that was present in the sample mixture; ideally the sample solvent flows through the column without interacting with the column, but is still detectable as distinct from the HPLC solvent.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The void volume is used as a correction factor.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Efficiency factor (*N*) practically measures how sharp component peaks on the chromatogram are, as ratio of the component peak's area ("retention time") relative to the width of the peaks at their widest point (at the baseline).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Peaks that are tall, sharp, and relatively narrow indicate that separation method efficiently removed a component from a mixture; high efficiency.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Efficiency is very dependent upon the HPLC column and the HPLC method used.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Efficiency factor is synonymous with plate number, and the 'number of theoretical plates'.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Retention factor (*kappa prime*) measures how long a component of the mixture stuck to the column, measured by the area under the curve of its peak in a chromatogram (since HPLC chromatograms are a function of time).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Each chromatogram peak will have its own retention factor (*e.g.*, *kappa*1 for the retention factor of the first peak).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This factor may be corrected for by the void volume of the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Separation factor (*alpha*) is a relative comparison on how well two neighboring components of the mixture were separated (*i.e.*, two neighboring bands on a chromatogram).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] This factor is defined in terms of a ratio of the retention factors of a pair of neighboring chromatogram peaks, and may also be corrected for by the void volume of the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The greater the separation factor value is over 1.0, the better the separation, until about 2.0 beyond which an HPLC method is probably not needed for separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Resolution equations relate the three factors such that high efficiency and separation factors improve the resolution of component peaks in an HPLC separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The internal diameter (ID) of an HPLC column is an important parameter.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] It can influence the detection response when reduced due to the reduced lateral diffusion of the solute band.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] It can also affect the separation selectivity, when flow rate and injection volumes are not scaled down or up proportionally to the smaller or larger diameter used, both in the isocratic and in gradient modes.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] It determines the quantity of analyte that can be loaded onto the column.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Larger diameter columns are usually seen in preparative applications, such as the purification of a drug product for later use.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Low-ID columns have improved sensitivity and lower solvent consumption in the recent ultra-high performance liquid chromatography (UHPLC).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Larger ID columns (over 10 mm) are used to purify usable amounts of material because of their large loading capacity.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Analytical scale columns (4.6 mm) have been the most common type of columns, though narrower columns are rapidly gaining in popularity.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] They are used in traditional quantitative analysis of samples and often use a UV-Vis absorbance detector.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Capillary columns (under 0.3 mm) are used almost exclusively with alternative detection means such as mass spectrometry.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] They are usually made from fused silica capillaries, rather than the stainless steel tubing that larger columns employ.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Most traditional HPLC is performed with the stationary phase attached to the outside of small spherical silica particles (very small beads).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] These particles come in a variety of sizes with 5 μm beads being the most common.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Smaller particles generally provide more surface area and better separations, but the pressure required for optimum linear velocity increases by the inverse of the particle diameter squared.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] According to the equations of the column velocity, efficiency and backpressure, reducing the particle diameter by half and keeping the size of the column the same, will double the column velocity and efficiency; but four times increase the backpressure.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] And the small particles HPLC also can decrease the width broadening.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Larger particles are used in preparative HPLC (column diameters 5 cm up to >30 cm) and for non-HPLC applications such as solid-phase extraction.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Many stationary phases are porous to provide greater surface area.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Small pores provide greater surface area while larger pore size has better kinetics, especially for larger analytes.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] For example, a protein which is only slightly smaller than a pore might enter the pore but does not easily leave once inside.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Pumps vary in pressure capacity, but their performance is measured on their ability to yield a consistent and reproducible volumetric flow rate.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Pressure may reach as high as 60 MPa (6000 lbf/in2), or about 600 atmospheres.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Modern HPLC systems have been improved to work at much higher pressures, and therefore are able to use much smaller particle sizes in the columns (<2 μm).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] These "ultra high performance liquid chromatography" systems or UHPLCs, which could also be known as ultra high pressure chromatography systems, can work at up to 120 MPa (17,405 lbf/in2), or about 1200 atmospheres.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The term "UPLC" is a trademark of the Waters Corporation, but is sometimes used to refer to the more general technique of UHPLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] HPLC detectors fall into two main categories: universal or selective.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] HPLC most commonly uses a UV-Vis absorbance detector; however, a wide range of other chromatography detectors can be used.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] A universal detector that complements UV-Vis absorbance detection is the charged aerosol detector (CAD).
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] A kind of commonly utilized detector includes refractive index detectors, which provide readings by measuring the changes in the refractive index of the eluant as it moves through the flow cell.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In certain cases, it is possible to use multiple detectors, for example LCMS normally combines UV-Vis with a mass spectrometer.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] When used with an electrochemical detector (ECD) the HPLC-ECD selectively detects neurotransmitters such as: norepinephrine, dopamine, serotonin, glutamate, GABA, acetylcholine and others in neurochemical analysis research applications.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] The HPLC-ECD detects neurotransmitters to the femtomolar range.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Other methods to detect neurotransmitters include liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry, ELISA, or radioimmunoassays.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] Large numbers of samples can be automatically injected onto an HPLC system, by the use of HPLC autosamplers.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] In addition, HPLC autosamplers have an injection volume and technique which is exactly the same for each injection, consequently they provide a high degree of injection volume precision.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p01] It is possible to enable sample stirring within the sampling-chamber, thus promoting homogeneity.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] HPLC has many applications in both laboratory and clinical science.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] It is a common technique used in pharmaceutical development, as it is a dependable way to obtain and ensure product purity.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] While HPLC can produce extremely high quality (pure) products, it is not always the primary method used in the production of bulk drug materials.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] According to the European pharmacopoeia, HPLC is used in only 15.5% of syntheses.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] However, it plays a role in 44% of syntheses in the United States pharmacopoeia.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] This could possibly be due to differences in monetary and time constraints, as HPLC on a large scale can be an expensive technique.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] An increase in specificity, precision, and accuracy that occurs with HPLC unfortunately corresponds to an increase in cost.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] This technique is also used for detection of illicit drugs in various samples.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] The most common method of drug detection has been an immunoassay.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] However, convenience comes at the cost of specificity and coverage of a wide range of drugs, therefore, HPLC has been used as well as an alternative method.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] As HPLC is a method of determining (and possibly increasing) purity, using HPLC alone in evaluating concentrations of drugs was somewhat insufficient.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] Therefore, HPLC in this context is often performed in conjunction with mass spectrometry.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] Using liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (LC-MS) instead of gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS) circumvents the necessity for derivitizing with acetylating or alkylation agents, which can be a burdensome extra step.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] LC-MS has been used to detect a variety of agents like doping agents, drug metabolites, glucuronide conjugates, amphetamines, opioids, cocaine, BZDs, ketamine, LSD, cannabis, and pesticides.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] Performing HPLC in conjunction with mass spectrometry reduces the absolute need for standardizing HPLC experimental runs.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] Similar assays can be performed for research purposes, detecting concentrations of potential clinical candidates like anti-fungal and asthma drugs.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] This technique is obviously useful in observing multiple species in collected samples, as well, but requires the use of standard solutions when information about species identity is sought out.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] It is used as a method to confirm results of synthesis reactions, as purity is essential in this type of research.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] However, mass spectrometry is still the more reliable way to identify species.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] Medical use of HPLC typically use mass spectrometer (MS) as the detector, so the technique is called LC-MS or LC-MS/MS for tandem MS, where two types of MS are operated sequentially.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] When the HPLC instrument is connected to more than one detector, it is called a hyphenated LC system.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] Pharmaceutical applications are the major users of HPLC, LC-MS and LC-MS/MS.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] This includes drug development and pharmacology, which is the scientific study of the effects of drugs and chemicals on living organisms, personalized medicine, public health and diagnostics.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] While urine is the most common medium for analyzing drug concentrations, blood serum is the sample collected for most medical analyses with HPLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] One of the most important roles of LC-MS and LC-MS/MS in the clinical lab is the Newborn Screening (NBS) for metabolic disorders and follow-up diagnostics.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] The infants' samples come in the shape of dried blood spot (DBS), which is simple to prepare and transport, enabling safe and accessible diagnostics, both locally and globally.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] Other methods of detection of molecules that are useful for clinical studies have been tested against HPLC, namely immunoassays.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] In one example of this, competitive protein binding assays (CPBA) and HPLC were compared for sensitivity in detection of vitamin D.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] Useful for diagnosing vitamin D deficiencies in children, it was found that sensitivity and specificity of this CPBA reached only 40% and 60%, respectively, of the capacity of HPLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/high-performance-liquid-chromatography-p02] While an expensive tool, the accuracy of HPLC is nearly unparalleled.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] In chromatography, the **retardation factor** (***R***) is the fraction of an analyte in the mobile phase of a chromatographic system.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] In planar chromatography in particular, the retardation factor ***R*****F** is defined as the ratio of the distance traveled by the center of a spot to the distance traveled by the solvent front.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] Ideally, the values for *R*F are equivalent to the *R* values used in column chromatography.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] Although the term ***retention factor*** is sometimes used synonymously with *retardation factor* in regard to planar chromatography, the term is not defined in this context.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] However, in column chromatography, the retention factor or **capacity factor** (***k***) is defined as the ratio of time an analyte is retained in the stationary phase to the time it is retained in the mobile phase, which is inversely proportional to the retardation factor.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] The retardation factor, *R*F, is commonly used in paper chromatography and thin layer chromatography (TLC) for analyzing and comparing different substances.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] An *R*F value will always be in the range 0 to 1; if the substance moves, it can only move in the direction of the solvent flow, and cannot move faster than the solvent.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] For example, if particular substance in an unknown mixture travels 2.5 cm and the solvent front travels 5.0 cm, the retardation factor would be 0.50.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] One can choose a mobile phase with different characteristics (particularly polarity) in order to control how far the substance being investigated migrates.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] An *R*F value is characteristic for any given compound (provided that the same stationary and mobile phases are used).
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] It can provide corroborative evidence as to the identity of a compound.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] If the identity of a compound is suspected but not yet proven, an authentic sample of the compound, or standard, is spotted and run on a TLC plate side by side (or on top of each other) with the compound in question.
[src:chromatography-methods/retention-factor] Note that this identity check must be performed on a single plate, because it is difficult to duplicate all the factors which influence *R*F exactly from experiment to experiment.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] It is performed on a TLC plate made up of a non-reactive solid coated with a thin layer of adsorbent material.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The sample is deposited on the plate, which is eluted with a solvent or solvent mixture known as the mobile phase (or eluent).
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] This solvent then moves up the plate via capillary action.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] As with all chromatography, some compounds are more attracted to the mobile phase, while others are more attracted to the stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Therefore, different compounds move up the TLC plate at different speeds and become separated.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] To visualize colourless compounds, the plate is viewed under UV light or is stained.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Testing different stationary and mobile phases is often necessary to obtain well-defined and separated spots.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] TLC is quick, simple, and gives high sensitivity for a relatively low cost.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] It can monitor reaction progress, identify compounds in a mixture, determine purity, or purify small amounts of compound.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The process for TLC is similar to paper chromatography but provides faster runs, better separations, and the choice between different stationary phases.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Plates can be labelled before or after the chromatography process with a pencil or other implement that will not interfere with the process.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The separation of compounds is due to the differences in their attraction to the stationary phase and because of differences in solubility in the solvent.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Different compounds in the sample mixture travel at different rates due to the differences in their partition coefficients.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Different solvents, or different solvent mixtures, give different separations.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The retardation factor (*R*F) quantifies the results.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] It is the distance traveled by a given substance divided by the distance traveled by the mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] In normal-phase TLC, the stationary phase is polar.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Silica gel is very common in normal-phase TLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] More polar compounds in a sample mixture interact more strongly with the polar stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] As a result, more-polar compounds move less (resulting in smaller *R*F) while less-polar compounds move higher up the plate (higher *R*F).
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] A more-polar mobile phase dissolves polar compounds more.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] As such, all compounds on the TLC plate move higher up the plate in polar solvent mixtures.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] "Strong" solvents move compounds higher up the plate, whereas "weak" solvents move them less.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] If the stationary phase is non-polar, like C18-functionalized silica plates, it is called reverse-phase TLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] In this case, non-polar compounds move less and polar compounds move more.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The solvent mixture will also be much more polar than in normal-phase TLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] An eluotropic series, which orders solvents by how much they move compounds, can help select a mobile phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Solvents are divided into solvent selectivity groups.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Using solvents with different elution strengths or different selectivity groups can often give very different results.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] While single-solvent mobile phases can sometimes give good separation, some cases may require solvent mixtures.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] In normal-phase TLC, the most common solvent mixtures include ethyl acetate/hexanes (EtOAc/Hex) for less-polar compounds and methanol/dichloromethane (MeOH/DCM) for more polar compounds.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Different solvent mixtures and solvent ratios can help give better separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] In reverse-phase TLC, solvent mixtures are typically water with a less-polar solvent: Typical choices are water with tetrahydrofuran (THF), acetonitrile (ACN), or methanol.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] TLC plates are usually commercially available, with standard particle size ranges to improve reproducibility.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] They are prepared by mixing the adsorbent, such as silica gel, with a small amount of inert binder like calcium sulfate (gypsum) and water.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] This mixture is spread as a thick slurry on an unreactive carrier sheet, usually glass, thick aluminum foil, or plastic.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The resultant plate is dried and *activated* by heating in an oven for thirty minutes at 110 °C.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The thickness of the absorbent layer is typically around 0.1–0.25 mm for analytical purposes and around 0.5–2.0 mm for preparative TLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Other adsorbent coatings include aluminium oxide (alumina), or cellulose.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] TLC is a valuable tool for reaction monitoring.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] For this, the plate normally contains a spot of starting material, a spot from the reaction mixture, and a co-spot (or cross-spot) containing both.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The analysis will show if the starting material disappeared and if any new products appeared.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] This provides a quick and easy way to estimate how far a reaction has proceeded.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] In one study, TLC has been applied to screen organic reactions.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The researchers react an alcohol and a catalyst directly in the co-spot of a TLC plate before developing it.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] This provides quick and easy small-scale testing of different reagents.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Compound characterization with TLC is also possible and is similar to reaction monitoring.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] However, rather than spotting with starting material and reaction mixture, it is with an unknown and a known compound.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] They may be the same compound if both spots have the same *R*F and look the same under the chosen visualization method.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] However, co-elution complicates both reaction monitoring and characterization.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] This is because different compounds will move to the same spot on the plate.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] In such cases, different solvent mixtures may provide better separation.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] A pure sample should only contain one spot by TLC.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] TLC is also useful for small-scale purification.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Because the separated compounds will be on different areas of the plate, a scientist can scrape off the stationary phase particles containing the desired compound and dissolve them into an appropriate solvent.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Once all the compound dissolves in the solvent, they filter out the silica particles, then evaporate the solvent to isolate the product.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Big preparative TLC plates with thick silica gel coatings can separate more than 100 mg of material.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] TLC is useful for larger-scale purification and isolation to quickly test solvent mixtures before running flash column chromatography on a large batch of impure material.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] A compound elutes from a column when the amount of solvent collected is equal to 1/*R*F.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The eluent from flash column chromatography gets collected across several containers (for example, test tubes) called fractions.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] TLC helps show which fractions contain impurities and which contain pure compound.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Furthermore, two-dimensional TLC can help check if a compound is stable on a particular stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] This test requires two runs on a square-shaped TLC plate.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] The plate is rotated by 90º before the second run.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] If the target compound appears on the diagonal of the square, it is stable on the chosen stationary phase.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] Otherwise, it is decomposing on the plate.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] If this is the case, an alternative stationary phase may prevent this decomposition.
[src:chromatography-methods/thin-layer-chromatography] TLC is also an analytical method for the direct separation of enantiomers and the control of enantiomeric purity, e.g. active pharmaceutical ingredients (APIs) that are chiral.
